 font-size:12pt"> and secure workforce for the future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I’m Carl Bennett the Managing Director of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Tradeskills4U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Ltd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We are the UK's largest educator of the electrical installation adult workforce and the country’s only specialist electrical IET ‘Centre of Excellence’, to put this into context, we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> actually a modest family run company employ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">30 people. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at we are is a business to business company with an enviable reputation and 98% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">candidate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">approval rating. We are an independent company; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">none</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> funded organization. Chairman Clive Betts MP and other MPs have visited our facilities.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We train approximatel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3000 adult candidates each year in a full range of electrical domestic, commercial and industrial skills and adult vocational qualifications, many for continuing professional development. We also train adult apprentices and Domestic electrical installers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to enable them to register on the various Competent Person’s Schemes. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our core candidates are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">75%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> existing electrical and other trade’s contractors and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">25%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> new entrants.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">95 %</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of our candidates are micro business owners and employers, essentially the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> backbone of the industry. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Like any good business, we constantly engage with our customers/candidates. Dozens are literally under our roof every day, many of them are electrical contractors and others not fully qualified electricians but are employed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">within the greater electrical industry because of their ability to work within the Competent Person Schemes, they have a wide range of experience in many other trades and also have competency in electrical installation to undertake that role as their main </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">occupation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">requires I.e. Heating engineers, kitchen fitters, home maintenance contractors, auto gate installers, gas engineer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the list is too numerous to be exhaustive within this space</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it’s my job to gather evidence, engage with and listen to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">opinions from every aspect of the wider industry of electrical installation to ensure we supply the right training, qualifications and skills options for employers, electricians, associated trades, companies and new entrants into the industry. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eople and their businesses are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">my</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">constituency,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have a well rounded and perhaps unique view of the domestic electrical installation, repair, maintenance, improvement, upgrade and service industry and in fact the wider issue of the ski</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lls level of the electrical industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">entitle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to express opinions and suggestions in contribution to your debate.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The electrical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> force</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, from an industry trainer’s perspective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is worth noting, the wider world of the electrical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> installation industry does not belong solely to the institutions of the Electrical Industry. The heating engineer who wires in your boiler is not in the electrical industry, the kitchen fitter, landscape gardener or home maintenance contractor is not in t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he electrical industry but nevertheless, everyday they, and many others like them, work quite competently and diligently with electrics.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This large group of stakeholders,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> certainly in their tens of thousands, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rival in numbers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to any of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organizatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that has spoken to you so far, rarely ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> opinions listened to by those with the power to steer the industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. These people must be considered in your deliberations.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Perhaps because we are an independent educator of the workforce, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able to offer observations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as educator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the workforce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that seem quite contrary to some of the view </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have heard expressed to you so far.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In particular our view of the supply of future workers to small employers is very definitely not a positive one.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> IET</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (Institution of Engineering Technology), o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ne of the world's largest organisations for engineers and technicians who have warned that proposed reforms to government funding could lead to a reduction in UK apprenticeships. We agree with IET claims </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that the reforms are likely to reduce quality and deter SMEs from taking part in apprenticeship schemes and have criticised apprenticeship reforms, saying that the changes would incur higher costs that may prevent smaller businesses from taking on apprenti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ces.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Edge Foundation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a leading independent education charity, pointed to the government's own research that suggests apprentice numbers could fall by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">73%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> when employers have to pay at least half the cost.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our views are also consistent with the views of Nigel Whitehead </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">UKCES</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Commissioner with regard to the future of our adult workforce and the recommendations he has made in his report of 8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> November 2013 to improve the vocational qualification structure of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our adult workforce to better reflect small employer’s needs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our op</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inion is that at the moment they do not.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Shortage of workforce supply.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It may surprise you to learn that the person that comes to your door to undertake some electrical work for you in your home is almost certainly going to be a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">properly qualified </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Competent Person and a member of a Competent Person Scheme. They are probably u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nlikely to be a so called ‘fully qualified electrician’. (That is a contractor who has served a full time traditional apprenticeship with a full set of qualifications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> i.e a Level 3 NVQ plus other qualifications</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) This is a fact that surprises many existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">electrical contractors who wrongly assume the ‘fully qualified electrician’ to be in the majority.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It is certainly our experience that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an increasing majority of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">electricians are ‘fully qualified’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> many hav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> failed to keep up with current regulations, tec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hnologies and changes in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">best </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">practices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Competent Persons keep the system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">working.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ur estimation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> gained from experience of the thousands of small contractor companies with whom we engage and is compatible with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> many electrical education and workforce reports I have seen and other business and training leaders in our sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have spoken</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> less than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">50%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of people who undertake electrical work in this country are what you might call ‘fully qualified elect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ricians’, the remainder are likely to be properly trained, qualified and experienced Competent Persons with a wide range of experience in many other trades who also have competency in electrical installations to undertake that role as their main occupation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> requires and I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">doubt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do a proper and safe job.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Frankly if it were not for Competent Persons undertaking electrical work by the tens of thousands, the electrical infrastructure of this country would be compromised and poorly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">serviced. There are not enough so called ‘fully qualified electricians’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Many more experienced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">than me I have heard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> argue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in fact there really never has been. Pre Part P we just didn’t monitor electrical work undertaken to any great degree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, lots of this relatively minor and domestically defined work went </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unseen, compared with today, where electrical work is more visible due to Part P regulations.     </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s my information and experience of our engagement with contractors that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">numbers of electricians with full qualifications are rapidly dwindling and set to reduce at alarming rates in the coming years. The JIB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (Joint Industry Board)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, state, in their latest Labour Report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2012 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of their 18,000 total membership, that only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">31%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ir </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">experienced members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have full qualifications. JTL </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(The industry’s largest NVQ trainer) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with whom we work closely stated to us</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in a recent apprenticeships meeting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that they expect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">52%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the experienced workforce to retire in the next 8-10 years. We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">also know that industry apprenticeships are down </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">20%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on last year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">JIB itself completed only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">seven</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) apprentices last year, staggering</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">certainly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not their fault in my opinion, it’s the qualification </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">route </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with which they work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is to blame</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I’m sure and hope you’re aware that just over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">90 % </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the electrical installation industry is made up of very small businesses, comprising typically of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very small teams of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> contractors, large employers account for no more than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">10%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the industry, yet seemi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ngly get much more than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">10%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the say in to how the industry is run.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> The entry routes for employment in the electrical industry are ‘not fit for purpose’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The purpose of apprenticeships and career routes into the industry are to secure and train the future workforce for the benefit of us all. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">They are not working as they should and this is relevant for your committee to consider because electrical workforce that operates under Part P is set to dwindle rapidly in coming years. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From a training provider’s perspective,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a single qualification s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ystem to enter the industry is ‘not fit for purpose’. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">entry to industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">qualification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">start at a level that is achievable for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">person to which it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">intended</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more innovative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in design</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> better reflecting the needs of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> modern society</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the small employer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, enabling them to manage an appropriate qualification for the role the new entrant worker or apprentice would fulfill.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Large companies and some of the traditional organization in the industry have a different view from small </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contractors particularly with regard to apprenticeships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the training of their employees</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I can tell you as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of an organization that probably trains more candidates for apprenticeships than m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> others you have heard from, that the Small empl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oyers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(the 90%)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> do not and cannot support the current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">qualification routes open to their potential staff. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Obviously</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> large employers are supportive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">large</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> budgets and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">spare </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">manpower</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> plus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the small contractor is competition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> what better way to remove competition than to starve them of staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The small employer/contractor tasked with the actual job of training, paying for the training as well as paying and employing and paying </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the majority of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">apprentices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supportive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hey can’t afford the time and cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, they do all they can do to keep their heads above water, never mind bear the responsibility of training up the future </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> force</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The purpose of entry qualifications into the industry are to attract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> secure a future workforce. At the moment they don’t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he modern face of the industry has changed since those supposed past halcyon days, big employers have gone in the numbers they once were. The training of the apprentices in any decent numbers now relie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s on the hard pressed micro businesses that are not geared up, and are neither skilled, nor economically viable enough to support a traditional apprenticeship </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">route to entry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which is seen by many in my sector as no longer ‘fit for purpose’, the numbers spe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ak for themselves. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The common reason for not supporting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the current entry qualification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 46.4pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="background-color:#c0c0c0; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> one size fits </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">qualification </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as entry to the industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">does not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reflect the needs of the small employer, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a full 3 year apprenticeship is too onerous a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">commitment, regretfully the current qualification r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eflects the needs of the few big employers.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 46.4pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="background-color:#c0c0c0; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current Electrical NVQ is academically challenging to the average person, as a result dropout rates are alarming.    </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 46.4pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not suitable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for adults. Adult l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">earners can’t afford to live on the low wages an apprentice gets paid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">over a protracted 3 years. H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e/she are likely to have dependents and commitments that don’t allow them to learn and work at the same time for a prolonged period.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 46.4pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Small businesses, have di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fficulty to support them giving cost,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">administration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> plus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are un</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">likely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to have the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relevant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to be able</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to convey knowledge to a student. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Competent Persons qualification v Full NVQ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">qualification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The training for full NVQ, please note, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, i.e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the skills and knowledge that a person is taught in a college</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, not the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">workbased a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and gathering of experience </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which follows</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> commonly called ‘an apprenticeship’.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The typical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">delivery of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in centre by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> FE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">College</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is one day a week for 3 years. For easy comparison if you took the same course full time, it would be of 16 weeks duration</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This covers everything from installation of sockets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in your home </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">substati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> down the road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, domestic, commercial and industrial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">owever it’s a one size fits all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and is designed for a 16-19 year old with zero transferable skills from other work experience. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Domestic electrical element within an apprenticeship qualification is of 8 weeks duration; again assuming you did it as full time training. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By no coincidence the new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">qualification </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘Level 3 certificate in Installing, Testing and Ensuring Compliance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of Electrical Installations in Dwellings’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that enables a person to become a Competent person comprises of 12 weeks full time </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, so well over and above that of an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NVQ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> qualification.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The assumption that Domestic Competency training is somehow inf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">erior to a Full </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NVQ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is incorrect and misinformed. The training for the Domestic element is equal if not superior. Also usually because the demographic for this qualification is a 24+ years adult and they bring other relevant skills with them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their compete</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncy is likely to be higher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="vertical-align:middle"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="vertical-align:middle"><p style="margin:0pt"><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAAABCAYAAAAfFcSJAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAALSURBVBhXY2AAAgAABQABqtXIUQAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==" width="1" height="1" alt="https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/images/cleardot.gif" /></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are not enough so called ‘fully qualified electricians’ in the UK to meet current and certainly not future </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">demand.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are not enough new entrants either younger persons or adults </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">joining the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to cover the current and future loss of labour. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current entry level is set too high and needs intermediate level. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Competency schemes are all that keeps the electrical infrastructure repaired, maintained, upgraded, amended, functioning e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tc. Remove these and there will be significant negative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> impact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The training and qualifications for competency schemes is good and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and certainly up to the grade required for the job role. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Electrical design of our Domestic System is inherentl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y safe and has become </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">so as a result of Part P Regs. Though better monitoring and public awareness is necessary.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Since inception of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Part P regulations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we have been able to monitor the majority of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> electrical work, previously it was chaotic and invisibl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is no evidence of Cowboys being an unequal part of Competent persons schemes compared to the traditional electrician. Cowboys are surely just dishonest people no matter what their status in the industry.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is lots of evidence and expert opinion that the current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">routes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">into</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the industry are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not ‘fit for purpose’. Is failing our new entrants, failing our small employers, failing our requirements of a secure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> force for the future. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">j)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many decision maker</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s in the industry I know agree with our opinions and suggestions, but fear expressing them in fear of alienating their traditional workforce.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Our suggestion of a Domestic Electrician Grade to ensure constant supply of workforce and progression entry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">into industry.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The one size fits all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">route into the industry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is flawed, too expensive and too </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">challenging for the person for which it is intended </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We suggest there should be properly understood and accepted multi grades of electricians. Each capable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of progressing to the higher level above.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e suggest an additional grade of electrician </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to sit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">between the Competent person and the Full NVQ Qualified electrician as below. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This would have the advantage of people entering the industry with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">qualification based on what job they would actually be doing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">then provides a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">manageable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cost effective stepping stone to progression for the Full qualification</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and by design naturally upgrades safety &amp; best </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We suggest three grades of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> persons allowed to undertake electrical work. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Each grade capable of progression.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Grades</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ascending </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">   </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Competent Domestic Electrical Installer.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> For allied </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">trades,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Heating engineer etc. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (As exists but with proper industry recognition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and mandatory registration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Domestic Electrician. Domestic only work. (A shorter more defined competence qualification to better reflect the role, based on achievement not length)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:8pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Approved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Electrician (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Comprising of Domestic, Commercial and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Industrial) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">          </span><span sty